"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of lethargy and exercise intolerance. She has no chest pain, ankle swelling or change in her bowel habits. She has no significant medical history apart from a laparoscopic cholecystectomy at age 42. She does not take any regular medications. She went through menopause at age 49 and is not using any form of hormonal replacement. She is a lifelong non-smoker and says she drinks now only a small amount of wine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 97 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell volume: 107.2 fL (80-96)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCH: 28.8 pg (27-33)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERDW: 13.9% (12-15)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 130 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 272 U/L (\u0026lt;40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 128 U/L (\u0026lt;35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGGT: 358 U/L (\u0026lt;38)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALP: 111 (40-150)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVitamin B12: 141 pmol/L (200-680)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFolate: 16 nmol/L (\u0026gt;7)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cirrhosis","Bowel cancer","Pernicious anaemia","Alcohol abuse","Chronic kidney disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic anaemia. The laboratory studies reveal a macrocytic anaemia with associated vitamin B12 deficiency, mild thrombocytopenia, and deranged liver function tests (LFTs) with elevated AST, ALT, and GGT - a combination most likely caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcohol abuse\u003C/strong\u003E. While this woman has denied using alcohol to excess, many patients will not admit openly to excessive use, and therefore this diagnosis should not be ruled out. It is very common for patients to deliberately understate the amount of alcohol they consume. Excessive alcohol intake causes anaemia via direct toxic effects on red blood cell production in the bone marrow and nutritional deficiency of vitamin B12 and folate. Serum reticulocytes and a peripheral blood smear are required to further differentiate megaloblastic from non-megaloblastic causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with macrocytic, non-megaloblastic anaemia; however, we would expect more severe aminotransferase derangement and other signs of liver dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBowel cancer\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes anaemia from gastrointestinal blood loss or anaemia of chronic disease, with a microcytic anaemia, which would not explain the macrocytosis or liver function abnormalities seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPernicious anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E tends to affect older patients and primarily causes anaemia from vitamin B12 deficiency. While B12 is slightly below the normal range in this case, the collection of other abnormal laboratory findings, particularly the liver function tests, make alcohol abuse a more likely cause of her presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E causes a normochromic normocytic anaemia from underproduction of erythropoietin and shortened red blood cell lifespan. It would not explain the macrocytosis or liver function abnormalities seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pattern of liver function test abnormalities, with AST higher than ALT and elevated GGT, is particularly suggestive of alcohol-related liver disease. This, combined with the macrocytic anaemia and mild thrombocytopenia, strongly points to alcohol abuse as the underlying cause, even though the patient reports only moderate alcohol consumption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alcohol abuse can cause a macrocytic anaemia.","LFTs showing elevated GGT and transaminases, with AST to ALT ratio \u003E 1 is indicative of alcohol-related liver disease.","Patients often underreport their alcohol consumption, making it important to consider alcohol abuse even when denied."],"references":["Kaferle J, Strzoda CE. Evaluation of macrocytosis. Am Fam Physician. 2009 Feb 1;79(3):203-8. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2009/0201/p203.html","Torruellas C, French SW, Medici V. Diagnosis of alcoholic liver disease. World J Gastroenterol. 2014 Sep 7;20(33):11684-99. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25206273/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93149"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2577"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93149"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-07T14:54:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-07T14:55:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2577"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111032"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"ta